{{Administrative levels and divisions of China sidebar}}
{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
A '''residential community''' is a [[community]], usually a small [[town]] or [[city]], that is composed mostly of [[residency (domicile)|residents]], as opposed to [[commerce|commercial]] [[business|businesses]] and/or [[industry|industrial]] facilities, all three of which are considered to be the three main types of occupants of the typical community.
Residential communities are typically communities that help support more commercial or industrial communities with [[consumer|consumers]] and [[workforce|workers]]. That [[phenomenon]] is probably because some people prefer not to live in an [[urban area|urban]] or industrial area, but rather a [[suburb|suburban]] or [[rural area|rural]] setting. For that reason, they are also called [[commuter town|dormitory towns]], [[commuter town|bedroom communities]], or [[commuter town|commuter towns]].
An example of a residential community would include a small town or city outside a larger city or a large town located near a smaller but more commercially- or industrially-centered town or city, for instance [[Taitou, Gaocun|Taitou]] in Gaocun, Wuqing, Tianjin, China.
== China ==
In the [[mainland China|mainland]] of the [[China|People's Republic of China]], a '''community''' ({{zh | s=社区| t=社區| p=shèqū}}), also called '''residential unit''' or '''residential quarter''' ({{zh | s=小区| t=小區| p=xiǎoqū| links=no}}) or [[neighbourhood]] ({{zh | s=居民区| t=居民區| p=jūmínqū| links=no}}) or '''residential community''' ({{zh | s=居住区| t=居住區| p=jūzhùqū| links=no}}), is an urban [[residential area]] and its residents administrated by a [[subdistricts of the People's Republic of China|subdistrict]] ({{zh | s=街道办事处| t=街道辦事處| p=jiēdàobànshìchù| links=no}}). Every community has a community committee, neighborhood committee or residents' committee ({{zh | s=社区居民委员会| t=社區居民委員會| p=shèqūjūmínwěiyuánhuì| links=no}}) and every committee administers the dwellers living in that community.
Shequ ([[Chinese language|Chinese]]: 社区) are community institutions, consisting of participating citizens and chiefs, the latter ones being installed by the central governance. Shequ represent an attempt to restructure the relationship between state and urban community in China.<ref>Heberer, Thomas/Schubert,Gunter: Politische Partizipation und Regimelegitimität in China. Band I: Der Urbane Raum, Wiesbaden: VSVerlag 2008, pp 15-24,47-70,189-203.</ref>
The [[social anthropologist]] [[Fei Xiaotong]] is considered the first to have proposed the introduction of the idea of shequ in China.<ref>Heberer, Thomas/Derichs, Claudia: Einführung in die politischen Systeme Ostasiens. VR China, Hongkong, Japana, Nordkorea, Südkorea, Taiwan (2): VSVerlag 2008, pp119-144.</ref> The introduction of shequ started after the collapse of the previously existing social institutions (''[[danwei]]'') during the mid-1990s. Shequ were supposed to relieve the state of certain duties and responsibilities by transferring them to citizens participating in the shequ. They take over responsibilities which in democratic states are assumed by organisations of the civil community.
